**Abstract:**
A major essay titled "La Coupure Epistemologique" (The Epistemological Rupture) examining the origins of critical reason in Greek philosophy. The document argues that philosophy began with Socrates and Plato as a shift from innocent to critical discourse, establishing contemplative discourse as the absolute opening to reality. It traces the development from Socrates through Plato to Aristotle, analyzing how the bifurcation between contemplation and action became intrinsic to the Greek philosophical project. The essay culminates in analyzing the medieval encounter with Aristotle, arguing the medievals condemned themselves to lose the battle against rationalism by submitting faith to the level of mere propositions.

**AI Recommendation:** Central theoretical essay on the epistemological rupture; essential for understanding the author's critique of Western rationality.

